Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Bring 3/4 cup water and 1 @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1} to a boil in a #small pot{}. Halve @Poblano Pepper{2} lengthwise; remove cores. Rub with a drizzle of oil. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Roast on a #baking sheet{} until soft, about ~{20%minutes}.

Once stock boils, add @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup} to #pot{}. Cover, lower heat, and reduce to a gentle simmer. Cook until tender, about ~{15%minutes}. Meanwhile, halve, peel, and dice @Yellow Onion{1}. Finely chop @Jalapeño{1}, removing ribs and seeds for less heat.

Heat a drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add onion and jalapeño (to taste). Cook, tossing, until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add 2 tsp @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp} (we sent more) and @Ground Turkey{10%ounce}, breaking up meat. Cook, tossing, until no longer pink, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove from heat.

In another #small pot{}, stir together half the @Crushed Tomatoes{1/2%box}, remaining @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1}, 1/3 cup water, remaining Southwest spice, and as much @Chipotle Powder{1%tsp} as you like (start with a pinch and go up from there). Season with salt and pepper. Place over medium-low heat and bring to a gentle simmer.

Once rice is done cooking, add to pan with filling. Toss to combine. Season with salt, pepper, and any remaining chipotle powder, if desired. Stuff poblanos with as much filling as will fit. Place in same pan, nestling in remaining unused filling.

> TIP: If your pan is not ovenproof, transfer mixture to a small baking dish at this point.

Drizzle sauce over stuffed poblanos. Sprinkle with @Monterey Jack Cheese{1/2%cup}. Bake in oven until cheese melts, ~{2-3%minutes}. Divide stuffed poblanos and filling from pan between plates and serve.